Republican strategy to hinder Obama's re-election
Republican leaders justified their policy by the need to fight electoral fraud.
Now, the Brennan Center considers this latter a myth and claims that electoral fraud is less common in the United States than the number of people who die due to a lightning fall.
In fact, Republican lawyers have found no more than 300 cases of electoral fraud in the United States in ten years.
One thing is certain: these new provisions will negatively affect the participation rate.
In that sense, these measures will partially undermine the American democratic system.
Unlike in Canada, the U.S. states are responsible for organizing federal elections in the United States.
And in that same line a majority of American governments promulgated, from 2009, new laws that hindered the process of registration or voting.
This phenomenon has spread after the November 2010 elections, which saw the increase of 675 new Republican representatives in 26 states.
As a result, during 2011 180 bills were introduced that restricted the exercise of the right to vote in 41 states.
The new electoral laws require voters to present an identity document with a photograph, in addition to a proof of American citizenship.
On the other hand, those laws reduce early voting periods, invalidate the right to register as an elector on the day of the poll and withdraw their right to vote to citizens with criminal records.
Prior to the 2006 elections, no U.S. state required voters to present a photographic identity document.
The state of Indiana was the first to demand it.
The Supreme Court of the United States confirmed in 2008 the constitutionality of the Indiana law.
Therefore, the Republican authorities hastened to extend this practice to other states.
In recent years, these authorities have supported bills in 34 states to force voters to present a photographic identity document.
It is important to keep in mind that, unlike what happens in Quebec, American citizens do not have a universal identity document, such as the Social Security Card.
In fact, 11% of U.S. citizens, i.e. 21 million people in the age of voting, do not have any photographed identity documents issued by a government agency in their state.
On the other hand, five million new voters in 2012 lack an identity document with those characteristics.
But, often, obtaining the required identity document costs more than a hundred dollars.
Thus, the new restrictions disproportionately affect young people, minorities and people with low incomes.
In fact, 25% of African Americans, 15% of people earning less than $35,000 a year, 18% of citizens over the age of 65 and 20% of voters between the ages of 18 and 29 do not have a photographic identity document.
And there are more.
In many states, students, the voters who vote the most for Democratic candidates, cannot use a photographic identity document issued by their institution.
Furthermore, those same states authorize members of fishing or hunting clubs that usually vote for republican parties to use documents issued by such clubs.
Before 2004, no state required proof of citizenship to vote.
Arizona was the first state to present this requirement.
Since 2011, a dozen states have adopted laws that require voters to prove that they are American citizens.
These measures are clearly aimed at limiting the Spanish vote.
Apparently two out of three Hispanic voters support the Democratic party.
On the other hand, Republican lawmakers backed in 2011 certain laws that abolished voter registration on the same day of the poll in eight states.
In addition, they limited the right of individuals and groups to create a service to help voters who wanted to register.
These restrictions have consequences.
For example, in the 2004 general elections, voter registration campaigns contributed to the registration of around 10 million citizens.
Measures taken since 2009 have resulted in the rate of registration of new voters falling in 2010 compared to 2006.
In addition, Republican lawmakers adopted laws in five other states that favored the reduction of the voting period in advance.
For example, in the 2008 Florida elections, 33% of the voters who voted in advance were African Americans, while the latter represented only 13% of the state's voters.
In the case of the Spanish, it was exactly the same.
These represent only 11% of the voters, which is equivalent to 24% of the citizens who vote in advance.
However, whites, who represent 76% of the electorate, represent only 46% of the citizens who vote in advance.
Of course, Democratic legislators and their supporters have fiercely opposed the adoption of laws that restrict voter registration.
In this regard, the Democratic governors have blocked several bills.
The U.S. Prosecutor’s Office intervened to suspend the most controversial laws.
The damage was partially reduced.
For example, only 16 of the 34 states adopted the law that required the presentation of a photographic identity document.
However, it is undeniable that the new rules adopted will complicate the exercise of the right to vote in 2012.
Democratic critics denounce the party character of the laws that have been voted, as it is clear that with them it is intended to influence 2012 results in key states.
A 2011 Brennan Center report shows that states that have adopted such laws represent 171 of the 270 votes needed in the electoral college to the presidency.
It is too early to say with certainty whether these legislative changes at the electoral system level will have a significant impact on the results of the 2012 presidential election.
One thing is certain: these new provisions will negatively affect the participation rate.
In this sense, the measures will partially undermine the American democratic system.
