I asked for advice from two experts.
In studies conducted in the United States, a high rate of contagion was detected among the sample groups, so it is difficult to interpret those data and make firm recommendations.
For its part, the European study showed a certain difference in mortality between patients who had been detected and those who did not.
The study, with a follow-up at the age of 12, also showed that there is between 30 and 40% chance of metastasis if the detection test has not been performed.
I recommend, therefore, the test from the age of 50, or from the age of 40 if your father has suffered from prostate cancer.
Men of African American descent have a higher risk index.
The key is to make a good decision once the cancer is detected.
There are aggressive cancers and other cancers that are indolent.
