Higgs boson in detail
The announcement of the likely discovery of the Higgs boson caused a great shock last summer, and rightly.
It is believed, in effect, that this boson is part of the mechanism responsible for the mass of all that exists in the universe, nothing more and nothing less.
What’s more, it’s the particle whose existence was predicted by the standard model: our best or “less bad” explanation of the nature and behavior of matter, which has not yet been observed empirically.
But for physicists it is not entirely clear that it is Higgs.
We know without a doubt that there is a new particle and that it is very similar to the Higgs boson predicted by the standard model.
Moreover, new data unveiled this week at a major physics congress held in Kyoto appear to confirm that it is, although more data is still lacking to be completely certain.
In any case, we assume that this is Higgs, as the chances of mistaking seem few.
There is, in this great world, a widespread and inevitable law that implies that two things cannot be found in the same place at the same time.
There’s no way to break that rule and don’t try too much, because it will end up hurting.
Although particle physics is a very complex world, it has been demonstrated that there is also a law of these characteristics in it: the Pauli principle of exclusion, which stipulates that two particles cannot occupy the same space at the same time if they are in the same "quantum state"; a "state" that consists, in large part, of some of its characteristics.
Physicists classify particles into two categories.
On the one hand, we find the good citizens called fermions, who wisely obey the Pauli principle.
And on the other side are the Bosons, a dirty panda of anarchists who have no respect for anything, or at least not for this principle, which means they can be found in the same place and at the same time.
According to the website The Particle Adventure of the Berkeley Laboratories, which, by the way, is extraordinary, the bosons are divided into two groups: the mesons, of which we will not talk here, and the "force particles", by which the great forces of nature propagate and with which the Higgs boson would be somehow related.
These bosons, I would emphasize here, are not the exotic beasts we might believe.
In fact, if you manage to read this chronicle, it is thanks to an extraordinary banal boson: the photon or the “light particle” that acts as the “messenger” of the electromagnetic force.
Indeed, when a particle with an electric charge accelerates or changes direction, it “disorder” the electromagnetic field in that precise environment; a little like when we throw a stone into a pond.
In this "disorder" a electromagnetic wave (from light, infrared, ultraviolet, etc.) is born, and this wave is nothing more than a photon; that is, one of the "force-carrying" bosons.
A more stable area
The same happens with the Higgs boson, with the difference that it is another field, the Higgs field, which needs to be "disordered" for this boson to appear.
Now, the Higgs field is much more stable than the electromagnetic field.To activate it, it is necessary to reach extremely high energies, a little like if it were a frozen pond in which only a thick rock could slip through the surface.
Therefore, it takes an immense particle accelerator such as that of CERN (the great hadron collider is a ring of 27 km of circumference!) to reach such energy levels.
The analogy with the electromagnetic field is a new tool that explains the relationship between the Higgs and the mass.
In fact, not all particles or materials interact with the electromagnetic field.
Some, like magnets, do, but others don’t: a piece of paper, for example, will never stick to the door of a refrigerator.
And in the same way, not all particles interact with the Higgs field: those that do have a mass, while the rest (like the photon, by the way), do not have it.
Now, what “can” all these investigations bring?” asks Mrs. Plamondon.
For science, this serves to verify the validity of the standard model (MS), and also allows physicists to scrutinize the differences between MS observations and predictions.
For their part, many are eager to find themselves, as the slightest difference could open a door to a “new physical” that tapes certain holes in the model.
This, it must be said, still has huge shortcomings, such as it does not offer any explanation regarding gravity (ups!) or dark matter, which makes up about 80% of the universe’s matter (other ups!).
But we have not found such differences at CERN so far.
repercussions
The repercussions of such research on our day-to-day are difficult to predict, but we don’t think we’re wrong to say it won’t have any.
In the early 1960s, laser pioneers in the labs did not suspect the revolution their work would bring.
They interviewed the scientific applications, but nothing more.
In fact, as the physicist Willard Boyle, who worked in the Bell laboratories, where the laser was invented in 1960, and who produced the first continuous laser (the first were pushed) in 1962, said, at first the laser was rather considered a "laboratory apparatus".
Imagine it...
In addition, applications can also come from all the instrumentation surrounding the research.
For example, Willard Boyle himself developed a light captor in 1969 in the course of his research into optics.
Although it was not at all its original intention, this captor now serves as an "eye" for all digital devices in the world, which earned him the 2009 Nobel Prize in Physics.
That does not mean, of course, that the activities of the LHC necessarily want to transform our lives, but that you never know...
Palliative care.The best way to die.Le Devoir
In his Commission Die in Dignity, Quebec recently debated the delicate question of the end of life.
The debate should be resumed soon as a bill is being prepared.
Now, within this essential domain, there is still a lot to be done.
He tried to see it closely.
Just a few weeks ago, Mr. L. lived alone in his Montérégie apartment.
The prostate cancer that was destroying him had given him a breath of two years.
“They had given me five years of life, but I’ve already lived seven,” she said, walking in her bed at the Victor-Gadbois palliative care center in Beloeil, where she arrived the day before.
“But it’s always a shock, we can’t be prepared for this,” he continues.
The illness has caused him devastation: a huge weakness that prevents him from going to the bathroom alone and even eating on his own.
Sitting in front of an appetizing lunch, he accepts resigned to be helped to eat.
Brave, he even smiles, talks to strangers who pay attention to him, brings him medicines and offers him a bath.
The courage of ordinary death.
“My greatest desire is that they cure my diarrhea, it’s humiliating,” she confesses.
A few hours later, the team found a cure for that evil.
“In the course of our lives we learn that a man is standing on his feet,” says Pierre Brodeur, a psychologist at the Victor-Gadbois Center.
Returning to your childhood, for certain people, is an unacceptable humiliation.
“This depends on the person’s ability to accept that regression,” he says.
Because, according to the opinion of most people working in palliative care, the great moments take place at the very heart of that regression.
All patients who enter the Victor-Gadbois palliative care center suffer from cancer.
They have a maximum life expectancy of three months.
In that state, the team of doctors and nurses surrounding them no longer offer the "healing" care.
The greatest fear of Ms. A., 89, is to die “conscious and drowned.”
But the illness has made her discover her children.
“I have good kids,” he adds.
“I don’t have any more wishes in this life,” she says, before accepting a mask to help her breathe.
And she expects, in the coming days, a last visit from her son who lives in Italy.
Victor-Gadbois offers, with a group of volunteers, body care and food assistance.
They are palliative care that is given when nothing else can be done.
To help make your death more comfortable.
In Quebec, we have one palliative care bed for every 11,700 inhabitants.
It’s very little, because we all know we’ll end up dying someday.
Here, life continues in the best possible conditions, explains Dr. Christiane Martel, one of the doctors of the center.
Whether at the level of physical, emotional or spiritual comfort.
The dying person is offered mouthwashes with brandy or Pepsi, according to demand.
Diabetics no longer have their sugar levels under control.
Death is part of everyday life.
Yesterday night we served a beer to Mr. X, who died in the course of the night.
This morning, his son finished his beer at the deceased’s feet.
“We help both patients and their loved ones,” says Nathalie Savard, director of care.
In the center of Victor-Gadbois the days pass without ever being the same.
Alongside a 94-year-old man who tastes his last family gathering in the yard, well placed between his pillows while everyone drinks to his health, a 36-year-old man dies tragically, surrounded by his parents, his wife and his two children, after having tried everything to survive.
"Six months ago, there have always been three to five beds occupied by people under the age of 45 who are sick with cancer," says Dr. Christiane Martel.
53% of the patients who are admitted to the Victor-Gadboisarrivent center come from their home and 47% from the hospital.
Access to Palliative Care
77% of Canadians simply do not have access to palliative care, i.e. care designed to relieve suffering when a sick person reaches the terminal stage of their life, whether at home, in the hospital or in a care centre.
And several organizations, such as the Victor-Gadbois Centre and the Grand Montréal Home Palliative Care Society, are almost exclusively specialized in the care of cancer patients.
It is precisely that large relative shortage in Quebec’s health care that makes many doctors specializing in palliative care fear the adoption of a law that regulates euthanasia and assisted suicide.
Since October, a manifesto signed by eminences of palliative care, such as Dr. Balfour Mount and Dr. Bernard Lapointe, has circulated to demonstrate their opposition to such an initiative.
According to Dr. Christiane Martel, Quebec’s healthcare system is not competent enough to ensure that anyone has the right to quality palliative care before they agree to proceed with euthanasia.
“Recently,” she says, “I’ve seen a patient spend 14 days in Emergencies suffering great pains without having done what’s needed to relieve her.
I’m afraid that patients want to die just because they don’t get proper care.”
And in parallel, many oncologists obstinate with their patients until the last day, despite the worst prognosis.
Hélène Richard’s hopes of survival were already low when she left a weak chemotherapy treatment.
“When I told my oncologist that I wanted to stop the treatment, she told me she was very sorry that I wanted to stop fighting,” she said.
“H, she had told me there was nothing else to do!”
There is no omnipotent care.
Dr. Martel believes that 90% of patients who request to die thank their caregivers for failing to meet their demands once their pain has been relieved thanks to a palliative care team.
But it must be said that palliative care is not absolutely omnipotent when it comes to pain treatment.
According to Elsie Monereau, director of palliative care at home at Grand Montréal, patients do not respond to pain treatments in 8% of cases.
At the end of life, doctors often resort to palliative sedation, which serves to sleep the patient until the moment of his death, either sporadically or permanently.
We cannot pretend that we do not understand this part of suffering.
More and more, the unrelieved disease will have the possibility of having that palliative sedation.
The sick who are not relieved all say the same: “I want to die.”
But that doesn’t necessarily mean “I want euthanasia,” but “I want to be relieved.”
