But in every exchange, a central authority controls and deals with changes.
With bitcoin, all network nodes are at the same time bookkeepers, verificators, currency issuers and buyers and sellers.
How does that network work?
Each transaction between two users is actually done between two email addresses in the form of email.
A user can choose a different address for each payment, thus ensuring anonymity.
A set of information linked to this transaction is signed electronically through a double-key encryption system.
The network can thus verify the authenticity of the transaction.
Thanks to the content of the file, it is also possible to ensure that the changes of bitcoins are recorded in the public account book, which is spread across the network.
The key milestone is to write that new transaction into that book.
This goes through the resolution of a mathematical challenge thrown to computers and the winner, a kind of provisional central banker, will have the privilege to add that complementary line.
It is a phase of file fragmentation, that is, of transforming a large file into a shorter and unique numerical footprint.
Computers "take" the new transaction and add a number before "tracing" the set.
The goal is to find the number that offers a particular footprint (more zeros at the beginning).
Once that number is found, the other nodes easily check that it is the good one.
The transaction is then indestructibly linked to the chain of sets of the other transactions; any modification would change the footprint.
If, to commit a fraud, a user would want to pay twice with the same money very quickly (in less than ten minutes), the network would only accept as valid one of the two transactions; the other would become orphan, since both have different footprints.
The computer that solves the challenge gets 50 bitcoins.
To avoid inflation, that reward is divided into two regularly, probably before the end of 2012.
The number of bitcoins in circulation is, therefore, limited to 21 million, but they are divisible to the one hundred millionth, leaving a wide margin.
The difficulty of this challenge is also revealed in each increase in computing power.
The life of the network already has its heights.
Websites that offer services for Bitcoin have been attacked and deposited bitcoins have been stolen.
“The fault used does not affect the same protocol,” says Pierre Noizat, who has just launched Paymium, a real currency payment company that uses the Bitcoin network.
The ECB also takes into account the possibilities of money laundering thanks to this anonymous service.
But cash has the same disadvantage.
Weight actors like Wikipedia reject payments of this type.
Others, such as the WordPress platform, accept them.
Recently, Adi Shamir and Dorit Ron, from the Weizmann Institute in Israel, analyzed the accounting book and showed that about 80% of bitcoins are not in circulation.
In November, the “gigant rebays” were launched.
“We exchanged $30,000,” rejoices Jon Holmquist, who works for Coinabul, which converts bitcoins into gold.
Pierre Noizat, author of a pedagogical book on that currency, believes in the potential of this technology in addition to the transaction network.
Their system, Paytunia, equals a credit card (in real currency) or contactless mobile payment, but uses Bitcoin to validate transactions, which thus come out cheaper.
The carrier, in addition, manages your identity and can therefore remain anonymous.
The system is easy to deploy in stores, which do not have to install new terminals or software.
It’s enough for them to provide an address that a phone can “photograph and recognize,” says Pierre Noizat, who claims to have thousands of users.
There is a general movement of revision of hierarchical systems by more horizontal systems.
“It will take a while for Bitcoin to impose itself, but in 2013 there could be a change,” he predicts.
Furthermore, in its report, the ECB plans to re-evaluate the various risks, now considered high, in the event that this currency succeeds.
