A Constitution with Forces in Egypt
It’s a new double or nothing of President Mohammed Morsi.
While Egypt is more divided than ever in terms of the constitutional declaration, which provisionally grants him full powers, he decided to play the whole for the whole.
It surprised everyone on Wednesday when it announced that the Constituent Assembly would vote on its final text the next day.
Just a week ago, the head of state had given the Assembly two more months to finish its work.
And two years ago Egypt has used a provisional text, several times modified, which weakens institutional stability and leads to judicial clutter.
This new initiative has only increased the fracture in the country.
For his opponents, the president persists in his "autocratic delusion" and continues to "betray his word" and "pisote the right".
Its supporters say it is a measure to more quickly end the institutional and political crisis and accelerate the transition process.
A referendum should be held in the next 15 days.
A very short period of time that forces the Brothers to give up their plan to explain the text, article by article, to the Egyptians.
For the president, it is also a way to regain popular and democratic legitimacy while the controversy causes ravages across the country.
Morsi seems convinced that Egyptians will vote in his favour, as he said in an interview with the American weekly Time.
Considering that that appeal has been voted very quickly, it contains an ultimatum for the Egyptian people: "or vote for my text or I hold full powers," powers that are supposed to end with the adoption of the Constitution.
It is in that strange atmosphere that 85 members of this Constituent Assembly, Islamist in its vast majority, voted on the text yesterday.
The majority of liberals did not attend the meeting.
In mid-November, just before the constitutional declaration, they had closed the door because they believed they could not make their points of view valid.
Representatives of human rights, religious minorities and civil society did the same.
In order for the necessary quorum to be reached, 11 people, replacement members, were added yesterday morning in a hurry.
Some of them are very close to the Muslim Brotherhood.
As expected, the articles voted unanimously.
The commentators are funny, on the other hand, the fact that one of the few discrepancies of the day has been expressed virtually at the time of prayer, so much so that several members of the committee came to think that the watch of the Constituent was wrong.
The text, which was still being voted yesterday, consists of 234 articles.
Article 2 of the Constitution of 1971, which stipulated that “the principles of Sharia constitute the main source of law.”
The Salafist parties, for whom the establishment of Islamic law is a fundamental claim, hoped that "principles" could be replaced with "norms", which would have allowed a stricter application.
For Islamists, that this article has not been modified is a guarantee of their goodwill and their respect for the other components of Egyptian society.
The liberals label it hypocrisy and consider it to be nothing more than an advertising trick.
According to them, the Islamization of the Constitution is done through other articles.
They refer, in particular, to Article 220, which confers to Al-Azhar University a consultative role, in particular for anyone who has to confirm its compliance with Sharia laws.
According to Egypt specialist Sophie Pommier, it is disturbing because “the people called to speak out are not elected and have no democratic legitimacy.
Here we see the premises of a theocracy.”
The fears of the liberals are also increased by the fact that the next rector of the university would be quite less moderate than the current one.
“For now, there is no concrete religious implication.
With this Constitution we are within the framework of the civil state.
Most of the jurists who have been working on that text are not ulemas but universities, some of them formed in the French system,” explains Alexis Blouet, who prepares a thesis on the Egyptian constitutional transition.
But he recognizes that there may be some ambiguity around Article 220, since the terms used imitate religious vocabulary.
“We refer in particular to the term iqh [Islamic jurisprudence].
And the question that could be raised in the future would be to what extent civil judges are competent to rule over all of this.”
Beyond its religious character, the text voted yesterday has received many criticisms that refer to the extended powers conferred on the President of the Republic.
The Muslim Brotherhood will claim that they are few compared to those during the previous regime.
Another conflicting point: the powers conferred on the army.
According to the desire of the military, the review of the defence budget will not be submitted to Parliament, but to a national defence council.
Neither will the prosecution of civilians in military courts be prohibited, as human rights associations have called for.
These also showed their concerns about the text, which they consider liberticid.
The crime of blasphemy remains and, from now on, insults are prohibited, which could have serious consequences for freedom of expression, especially for the press.
Moreover, no article emphasizes the protection of women, emphasizes Heba Morayef of Human Rights Watch.
According to her, the only positive thing was the prohibition of torture in accordance with Article 36.
This was not mentioned in the previous Constitution.
Although the Egyptian president was scheduled to come out last night on television, protests are scheduled for noon.
Supporters of the head of state protested on Saturday.
In Israel, Ukrainian tourists are waiting for the Holy Land, the umbilical of the world and a sea of salmon
The Promised Land combines the majesty of biblical truths with modern comfort and a pristine nature.
“AIF” identified the five most important reasons why you should visit Israel.
Reverence in the Holy Land
Visit the Jordan River where Jesus was baptized.
It is believed that anyone who enters this "baptism stack" will receive divine grace.
And Galilee, the place of Jesus’ miracles: the conversion of water into wine at the wedding, walking on the waters, the calming of the storm and the filled nets.
In this same place, Jesus appeared to His disciples after His resurrection.
Most of the holy places are in Jerusalem.
Believers travel here through the Viacrucis or the Way of the Cross of Jesus (in Latin "Vía Dolorosa").
It begins at the Fortress of Antonio, the Pretory, where the judgment was held, and continues through the streets of the Old City, goes to the Holy Sepulchre on Mount Golgotha, the place of the crucifixion, to the Stone of the Unction and to the place of Jesus’ burial.
In this same place is also the symbolic Christian Blitz of the world, which symbolizes the salvation of humanity.
And the monastery of the Holy Cross in Jerusalem, built in the place where, according to a Christian legend, there was a tree from which the cross was made for the crucifixion of Jesus.
In Jerusalem is also the most sacred place for the Jews, the Wall of Lamentations; the remains of a temple destroyed by the Romans in the year 70 AD.
As is tradition, people of different religions leave here notes with their wishes, which will then become reality.
A vertical journey
The ruins of the Masada Fortress were what remained of a secret refuge against the enemies, which Herod the Great ordered to build in the year 25 BC for his family.
They are found in the mountain cliffs at an altitude of 450 m above sea level.
And to get there by their own means, only those who engage in the climb can.
Others can reach this historic summit at the funicular.
And in the north of the country at an altitude of 1600-2040 m is the famous Hermon ski resort, where in the winter months there is a large influx of tourists.
Until there, from the foot of the hill bus services are offered.
The total length of the ski runs is 45 km.
According to an ancient legend, on the top of the mountain supposedly inhabited pagan gods.
Visiting unique museums
There are about 300 museums in this country.
You cannot visit them all in one trip.
But it is worth visiting at least five of them, the most interesting.
Among them is the Museum of Israel, located near the Knesset (Israeli Parliament).
In it are preserved the ancient Dead Sea Manuscripts or Qumran Rolls, discovered in the caves of the desert of Judea, and around 500,000 archaeological and anthropological pieces.
It is worth visiting the Art Museum in Tel Aviv.
In its exhibition of paintings it has paintings of Impressionists and Expressionists such as Monet, Pissarro, Renoir, Cézanne, Sisley, Matisse, Modigliani, Chagall or Picasso.
In Acre you can visit the museum-bad Al Basha, which are some rooms of ancient Turkish bathrooms with model figures of visitors and bathers of that time.
In Cesarea it is worth passing through the exclusive private Ralli museum, where you can admire the sculptures of Rodin and Dalí.
There are no tour guides or souvenir shops.
Entrance is free and donations are not accepted.
The fifth, the Holocaust Museum or Yad Vashem in Tel Aviv, shows one of the most dramatic pages in history.
The most tragic section is the Children’s Memorial, built in memory of the 1.5 million children killed in concentration camps and gas chambers.
You enter it and find yourself in absolute darkness.
The stars shine.
And they sound the names of the Jewish children and the names of the countries in which they lost their lives.
Ukraine is also mentioned.
health
The three main tourist areas of Israel are located on the shores of the Mediterranean Sea, the Red Sea and the Dead Sea.
In each of them there are swimming pools, water parks, dolphinaries and oceanographic museums.
It is curious that in the Red Sea they are bathed even in the winter months, as the water temperature does not fall from 21 degrees and the air warms up to 23 degrees.
The Dead Sea is even warmer and they are bathed there all year round.
By the way, this sea, the most extraordinary in the world, is located at the lowest point on the planet: 417 m below sea level.
The blue waters there are a salmon that easily sustains even those who do not know how to swim.
The surroundings of the area are truly beautiful.
People come here to take treatment courses with saltwater, saltwater and curative clay and strengthen their health in cases of dermatitis, allergies, asthma, eczema, arthritis, bronchitis, diabetes and to put in order their broken nerves.
Playing the Mysteries of Antiquity
They are preserved in the ancient part of Tel Aviv, the Jaffa citadel, on the Mediterranean coast.
It was the famous sea route that connected Egypt, Syria, Anatolia and Mesopotamia.
The city is mentioned in ancient Greek and Egyptian legends.
According to legend, it was here that Noah built his ark and Perseus rescued the beautiful Andromeda with whom, in this same place, he led a long and happy life.
Tourists love to stroll through the narrow streets that carry the names of the Zodiac signs.
They say that if you touch the walls on the street of your "same" symbol, fortune will be favorable to you.
In Jaffa you can find couples of newlyweds who come from all over Israel, and even from other countries to photograph themselves.
And in Caesarea, the city of King Herod, you can stroll through the Roman theatre, "take" the fortress of the Crusaders.
In Roman times, Caesarea was the main city of Judea and the residence of Roman procurators, including Pontius Pilate.
The theatre, carefully restored, is now used for night concerts and opera shows.
The tourists remember
If you’re traveling to Israel, don’t worry if your English leaves much to be desired: in this country around 30% of the population speaks Russian.
The money for this trip is not recommended to carry it in euros, but in dollars, which can be easily exchanged for shekels (currently 1-3$,8 shekels).
Urban transport is mainly made up of buses, but in Jerusalem there is fast tram and in Haifa there is the only metro line in the country, which consists of six stations and connects the Lower City with the Upper City.
In fact, it is from a underground funicular.
Traveling in any type of public transportation costs 6 shekels and for this price you can travel by transbording for 1.5 hours.
In Israel, according to Jewish tradition, the Sabbath is celebrated on Saturdays.
From Friday night to Saturday sunset, markets and shops close and public transport interrupts their work.
But Sunday morning begins a new working week.
In many cafes, restaurants and hotels only kosher food is served, which excludes pork, seafood, fish without scales and dishes in which milk and meat are combined.
There is a wide selection of dishes based on cow and lamb meat, soups and desserts prepared with coconut milk, the traditional Hebrew cream called hummus, a wide variety of sauces, the faláfel, which are molten garbage balls, fruits and vegetables.
On the streets of Israeli cities there are no street dogs.
Instead, there are a lot of well-fed cats that “go to their taste” in an imposing way.
At night you can see them sleeping even on the roofs of parked cars.
The snorkelers love the crowded places and do not reject sweets.
Renting a car, depending on the brand, will cost from $37 (Hyundai Getz) to $188 (Audi A6, Volvo S80) per day.
In addition to the insurance, it costs $15 a day.
And renting a bicycle will cost you 15 shekels a day.
Tickets to the museums cost an average of 30 shekels.
Israel in figures
In 2012, more than three million tourists from around the world visited Israel.
Most of those arriving to travel and rest were citizens of the United States, Russia, France, Germany, Italy, the United Kingdom and Ukraine.
The Promised Land, from January to October 2012, was visited by 118,8 thousand Ukrainian tourists, an amount that exceeds 51% to the same index of 2010, before the cancellation of the visa regime on February 9, 2011.
"The great and powerful" will take you to Moscow: immigrants save for the language
As MPs and human rights defenders discuss the consequences that the law on compulsory examination would bring, timers have already appeared in the country that trade with “false” certificates.
Every year, 13 million immigrant workers arrive in Moscow, St. Petersburg and other Russian cities.
Most of them are citizens of Central Asian countries: Uzbekistan, Tajikistan and Turkmenistan.
Their only goal is to make money to help their families who have stayed at home.
From December 1, a law comes into force, according to which every working immigrant must undergo an examination to verify their knowledge of the Russian language.
For now, this rule is applicable only to those who intend to work in the service sector, community service institutions, household services and retail.
However, over time, as promised by the Federal Immigration Service, examinations will become mandatory for all immigrants.
Moreover, it will not be enough to pass the exam of the language, if not also the exam of Russian history and the exam of foundations of legislation.
Knowledge of the language must be confirmed even to receive and renew the work permit.
Exceptions are citizens of countries where Russian is the official language.
This law does not apply to persons who obtained their education certificates and diplomas before the dissolution of the Soviet Union in 1991.
Utility, fatality and defense of rights
The network of examining centres will operate under the auspices of the Pushkin Institute of Russian Language, the University of Friendship of the Peoples, the Moscow State University, the St. Petersburg State University and other Russian higher education institutions.
Immigrants will be able to apply for the tests in all cities, now in Russia more than 160 centers of this type are open.
The initiative on the introduction of the examination was supported by the deputies of the State Duma and the Federal Immigration Service.
But rights defenders, long before the law came into force, managed to ask the press this question many times: And what will this actually bring?
What changes will the mandatory knowledge of the language bring, both for Russians and for immigrants themselves?
First, respond representatives of the Immigration Service, this will allow to reduce the number of people suffering from "labour slavery".
Many people are talking today about defending the rights of labor immigrants, explains Víctor Sebelev, head of the representation of the Russian Federal Immigration Service in Tajikistan.
The defense of your rights must begin before your departure.
Only an organized selection system will solve the problem of immigrant workers in 90% of cases.
The problems are the immigrants without profession, education, those who do not know the language or pass the medical check.
Without understanding the language, says Sebelev, the future immigrant will be condemned to find scrupulous people who, under the pretext of helping, take a “paid trip” to a frightening and narrow cowboy, where he and dozens of others like him are consumed for months without food or documents, working 12 to 14 hours a day.
We have received many complaints from our immigrants.
"They are promised one thing in their homeland, but when they arrive they are deceived, they are deprived of their passports, they are not paid the promised salaries," said Tolib Sharipov, head of the labor immigration department of the Tajikistan Immigration Service.
Don’t be angry, my boss!
However, in the meantime, many citizens of Central Asian republics who wish to work in Russia recognize that they not only do not know the language of the country they intend to go to, but also in their own language write with difficulty.
Of course, this is not so much their fault, but their own misfortune: there are few Turkmen, Uzbek, Tayikos who can afford to receive normal primary education.
This is because their families don’t even have anything to feed the children, not to mention dressing them, shoes and buying them what they need for school.
When they reach adolescence, these boys venture to work at the first opportunity.
It’s hard, if you don’t know the language, you recognize them.
“One feels humiliated and inferior.”
However, when it comes to the language law, rights defenders point out an important point.
The examinations will be carried out only for those immigrants whose status is legal.
If they do not have that status, there will be no exam and consequently no official work.
Meanwhile, most immigrant workers still live in Russia illegally.
"Welcome or forbidden the passage to strangers"
Many visitors claim that getting the official status in our country is not so easy.
The cause lies in the bureaucratic obstacles and in the difficulties of the language itself.
In addition, legalization costs money: from twelve thousand to sixteen thousand rubles.
However, a fake inscription can be made quickly and for only one thousand five hundred rubles.
Russian police employees know that we usually carry fake documents, we are not registered and cases of extortion appear.
"We are asked for a hundred or two hundred rubles for cigarettes or tea," Umed Hushkadamov, a citizen of Tajikistan, told reporters.
“Go, don’t be foolish, buy a painting.”
On the first day of the entry into force of the language law, it became clear that not only immigrant registration documents can be fake.
Several “false” certificates of knowledge of the language have already been seized by federal immigration officials.
The counterfeit documents had been printed on standard color printers.
Of course, they came to the hands of the new owners not as a gift: each immigrant, wishing to facilitate the task of passing the tests, paid for the document seven thousand rubles.
This is two and a half times more expensive than the official examination procedure, which will cost the immigrant worker three thousand rubles.
The main task for the near future is to protect the system against corruption so that "diplomas" cannot be bought, government officials and rights defenders converge.
So far, authorities can promise immigrant workers who could not have successfully passed the exam the first time more time to study the basic course of the language.
In addition, immigrants who do not speak Russian will be offered jobs that do not require active communication with people.
