Employees of fast food restaurants and supermarkets in the United States are on strike.
Up to a quarter of U.S. teenagers find their first jobs as cash managers at McDonald’s
In recent days, a wave of protests has begun in the United States against low wages paid in Walmart’s supermarkets and in restaurants of popular fast food chains such as “McDonald’s”, “Burger King”, “Taco Bell”, “Wendy’s” and “Kentucky Fried Chicken”.
For now, no one dares to assert whether or not this wave will reach the nine points, or if it is destined to lose forces and rush into its early stages.
The protests are supported by trade unions and a number of left-wing NGOs.
In addition to the modest wage increases perceived by Walmart workers and those of the fast food system, the goal of the organizers of the protests is the creation of labor unions in these companies.
For now, this sector of the economy has virtually not been occupied by the trade union movement.
Forty-six cents a year?
The actions began last week, after Thanksgiving Day, the so-called “Black Friday.” That day, in the United States, the orgia of discounts captured millions of inhabitants, and sometimes accompanied by clashes.
That day, some workers in the Walmart corporation, which employs 2.2 million people worldwide, left their jobs and formed piquets of protest alongside leftist unions and activists in the corporation’s stores, whose products are aimed at people with modest and moderate incomes.
Walmart sells everything from pans, hunting rifles and car batteries, to vacuum cleaners, eggs and milk.
The products in their stores are on average between 8% and 27% cheaper than those in the larger supermarkets.
That’s why many poorly paid Walmart workers only buy at work.
The availability and range of products have made Walmart one of the largest corporations in America.
According to the words of two critics, Walmart can afford the luxury of selling products at very low prices, in part because it pays little to its workers.
The latter also complain of poor working conditions, such as the lack of mount loads or hand scanners.
That "Black Friday" demonstrators demanded wage increases and complained that the cost of health insurance provided by the corporation went from $30 to $100 monthly.
For a typical Walmart worker, who gets $9.5 an hour, this spending is excessive, they said.
Scientists at the University of California in Berkeley argue that if Walmart raises the average salary to $12 per hour, this will cost the corporation $3.2 trillion.
This is approximately 1.1% more than they spend on salaries now.
If Walmart puts the salary increase on the shoulders of consumers, each visit to the store will result in only 46 cents more.
In a year they will spend the ridiculous amount of $12.39 more than they spend now.
Walmart supporters say they are pleased that the protest took place only in nine states and that it caused no losses to the corporation.
The “Black Friday” lasted in its stores from 8 p.m. on Thursday until midnight the next day, and during that time, Walmart sold around 5,000 items per second.
In total, their cash registers conducted the "Black Friday" almost 100 million transactions.
The company's representative, Dan Fogelman, said in an interview with the leftist Huffington Post website that "less than five" Walmart employees left their jobs and that the protest had been nothing more than "another public relations trick", organized by the workers' union.
“Free box!”
The protests continued this week in New York, where the targets were not precisely the large Walmart stores (which in this progressive city do not appreciate them, and therefore for now there are none), but the "McDonald's" and other cheap restaurants.
McDonald’s says it sells billions of servings, and then they don’t even give you a sick leave and don’t pay you for your honest work!
Jumaane Williams, Member of the New York City Council
Currently, according to federal and New York law, the minimum wage is $7.25 per hour.
Fast food restaurants are increasing over time, but only slightly, and on average, ordinary workers in New York receive $8.90 an hour.
No one earns less than you in this country.
How it is possible to survive in New York with that money, for me is something incomprehensible.
There was a time when a quarter of U.S. teenagers went through McDonald’s and worked there, behind the bars, part-time after school, though they still lived with their parents.
Few saw this as the main source of income or planned to stay there for a long time.
Now, I constantly stumble upon some interviews with McDonald’s workers who complain that they have to live on this salary, and sometimes even feed their children.
On the other hand, in a Wall Street Journal forum there is a comment whose author notes that it is irresponsible to have children if you don’t know what to feed them with.
Participants in the protests, which began at 6:30 a.m. on Thursday at McDonald's on 40th Street and Madison Avenue, demanded that cashers and fast food chefs start paying at least $15 an hour, or double their current minimum wage.
They also demanded that workers’ unions be created in the fast food sector.
U.S. law prohibits the administration from preventing them from this right and punishing trade union activists with slanders and dismissals.
However, administration rarely makes life easier.
But, for objective reasons, it’s easy for unions to embrace the fast food sector.
One of the main causes is the excessive rotation of staff.
Discordantly
Noisy protests took place that same day at other cheap restaurants in Manhattan.
The culmination of the action took place in the middle of the rally at McDonald's near Times Square, in which several local Democratic politicians participated, in particular the city council member Jumaane Williams, who said: "McDonald's says it is selling billions of servings, and then it doesn't even give you a hospital or pay you for your honest work."
The protesters received the support of other prominent New York Democrats, such as New York City mayoral candidate Bill de Blasio, who said that “we must support fast food workers to get the fair wages and economic prosperity that every New Yorker deserves.”
As described by the New York Times, this has been the largest manifestation of this kind in American history of fast food.
But only a few hundred people took part in it, not all of them were employees of the fast food service, in which tens of thousands of people from New York work.
It is not yet clear whether this will serve as a spark to provoke a mass movement.
“For now, deceiving the brain isn’t that easy.”
The theme of augmented reality, so popular among fans of modern technologies, has recently been normally perceived mainly through the prisma of special glasses.
At the beginning of the summer, at its annual conference Google demonstrated a model in motion and subsequently, in November, it was known that Microsoft had also submitted a request to claim the corresponding patent.
However, from a conversation with the head of the 3D interactive technology group at Microsoft's Cambridge laboratory, Izadi Sharamom, it was clear that for the scientists of the company, glasses already belonged to a past stage.
They are attracted by the perspective of manipulating virtual objects in the air with bare hands and creating open virtual spaces.
- Please, in general terms, what is the study object of your research group?
We dedicate ourselves to person-computer interaction, but we also try to broaden the boundaries of this interaction.
For now, humanity in its vast mass has been trapped in the stage of working with the flat-screen pixels, sometimes touching it with the finger.
But we want to look 5-10 years ahead and guess the cardinal changes in this interaction.
For example, the Xbox console and Kinect sensors represent a step forward and today no Xbox is sold without Kinect, as everyone is interested in gesture control.
What else does the future tell us?
Although Kinect has brought interaction to the physical level, much of it still occurs on a flat screen, sometimes in 3D.
The information input has improved (the system receives more data), and the output is still not very good.
We’re trying to change this, we’re working on truly three-dimensional visualization systems, based on different technologies, including design ones.
The computer world must be liberated from our own, the physical, to make it more tangible.
For this, however, it is necessary to recognize not only the user, but also the space surrounding him.
Then we can complete the real world with virtual objects in a more convenient way.
First of all, hell with those foolish virtual reality helmets!
What do you think about voice control?
A very popular detail, but don’t you think they’re overestimated?
- Of course, it cannot be considered a panacea, it remains pending to resolve the privacy issue, since it is not always wanted to let others know about our actions and intentions.
In fact, all types of interaction with computers are good, but each in its own field.
For example, for the control of devices in public places, we had a project in which we thought of gestures, but not loose movements, but shorter ones.
In addition, the gestures were captured not by the camera of the device, but by a bracelet that recorded the movement of bones and muscles.
For now it is very large, but in theory it can be reduced to the size of a wristwatch.
But, in general, the future is for a combined type of control, for example gesture + voice.
How is that?
- For example, how would you ask me to pass this bottle of soda?
You will speak and show it at the same time.
Usually I just talk.
That will be very difficult to recognize.
That is, do you want to force users to adapt to what the machine can or can’t do right now?
Not necessarily, but it is a mutual approach.
I think in the near future we will have to work mainly on designing new types of sensors that can accurately determine the reactions of the person.
These can be, for example, laser sensors, as they provide a good depth resolution, which is very important.
If we talk about your work with Xbox Kinect sensors, what complaints do you have about modern cameras?
Do you lack resolution, depth or something else?
In principle, the current generation is what can be the beginning of our work with three-dimensional recognition.
Of course, it would be good to get 8 megapixels at the speed of 1000 fps.
But the issue is not in megapixels, but in the quality of the matrix and in the depth.
From this latter point of view, not all current technologies are good enough for us; this gives more work to algorithm designers.
That is, we have to remember not only the resolution in the axes X and Y, but also in Z.
Also important is the speed, the number of frames per second.
Human movements are quite dynamic and the current 30fps are really scarce, especially for gestures.
Steven Bathiche, from our lab in Redmond, made a touch sensor with adjustable processing delay of 1 to 100 ms and it is worth mentioning that modern series-produced sensors are closer to the second value (60-100).
Not everyone understands to what extent this affects human-machine interaction.
I would be very useful for my work an equivalent of such a device, but that does not require contact so that the frames per second are more.
Do you need to increase the number of cameras?
The Kinect now has three “cams”, one of which is actually the infrared emitter and the second is the receiver of the reflected signal.
But the third camera is actually a simple visible slide sensor.
This is not used to determine the depth of the object.
More cameras could solve the problem.
Or, on the contrary, increase it and increase the required amount of calculations.
It would be nice to create a flexible analogue of Kinect, play with the location curvature of the cameras and see how this would help determine the three-dimensional position.
As far as I remember, Microsoft, unlike Google, has not presented its glasses to the public.
Do you not think that from the point of view of everyday use of augmented reality technologies, glasses are one of the most visible platforms?
- Of course, spending all the time holding up a smartphone in your hands, is not very comfortable, but I think: the best option would be an "transmutable" augmented reality when, based on a cloud platform, you could switch from glasses to a smartphone,
Glasses are very personal devices, in that is their strength (private things only you can see them), but also their weakness: an augmented reality based on glasses will not allow you to work on virtual objects alongside other people.
- Imagine for a moment that the manipulation of virtual holographic objects in the air is available not only for Tony Stark of the movie "Iron Man", but also for any simple mortal.
There is a problem in this idea that critics often point out: there is no touch response!
My hands feel nothing.
What answers is your team preparing for this challenge?
In my lectures I often say that augmented reality is the seventh breakthrough in the interaction between man and machine.
I think the eighth well could be the addition of tactile sensations.
Meanwhile, one of the most interesting tricks is the use of second hand as a support for the image.
Capture the touch perfectly!
But there are also technologies that are truly oriented to bring tangibility to these "images in the air".For example, the interference of several ultrasonic rays directed to a specific point where the finger is located gives a similar feeling to what one feels if someone was blowing him in the thumbs of the fingers, but that feeling is still very weak.
There are also wristbands for the wrist that influence the nerve endings of the fingers, this is also a promising direction.
Have you tried to fool your brain?
Make him think he feels what he seems he should feel in the moment he sees something?
That’s a good idea, I haven’t tried it yet.
Here lies another challenge that we will have to struggle with for a long time, how to make a person physically located in a very small space believe that he goes to an open space, almost endless.
For now, deceiving the brain is not so easy, you still have to work for many years.
That’s what makes working with virtual reality attractive for researchers, that many things are in a state of total conception.
