At the meeting of the control committee in the Congress of Deputies, you talked about the joint project between the Czech and German teams, within which the legislation on public procurement in both countries was compared.
What is exactly?
This is a parallel control that we started doing about two years ago.
Simplified: European legislation regulates how public procurements should be organized, followed by the legislation in force in each country and then by the practice itself.
We have united everything and, although the control has not yet ended, we have obtained very interesting differences.In general, the legislation of our country is "stricter and more comprehensive", however, the concrete practice in some parameters is better in Germany.
It is confirmed, therefore, that it is not enough to incorporate increasingly strict rules, but that it is necessary to focus on the application of the law itself.
What can this project actually bring? what do you think the conclusions are?
