Could it be better, for example, in terms of the quality of the inspectors?
I’m sure not, but I don’t like to make such comparisons.
It is necessary to say that even those countries that we take as a model must face a large number of problems.
If that were not the case, you’t have any benefit from collaborating with our office, don’t you think?
As for the legislation of our country, what did the amendment to the law on public procurement mean for your Office?
Given that the period of validity of this amendment is relatively short, it has not yet been manifested in the control actions.
Since we do ex-post checks, we need to count on a certain delay.
For now, it is observed in the process of preparing for future controls: we have initiated a new tool of "detection of non-economic risks", by which we have passed almost 14,000 public procurements, which have been analyzed.
Do you consider that the approval of this law is beneficial, or is it rather a mess for the bureaucratic system?
I think this law is a step in the right direction and I hope it will be.
The problem that may arise is that the regulations “harden” and that it is impossible to comply with them.
Already with the previous regulations, the controlled persons were linked to the contractor (for example, in the case of the regional operational programmes of the regional council), and each non-respect in public procurement law meant a violation of budgetary discipline.
Does it make sense to tighten the law in this way?
I think not in this way.
The system should exclude those who want to attack it or take advantage of it and not punish those who commit a formal failure, which has no impact on decision-making.
Such a system will only create more bureaucratic pressure.
How do you get out of this?
We will see where this path leads.
The prime minister has recently stated that the SDG would not bother entrepreneurs with controls of the so-called švarc system, referring to the fact of being autonomous only on paper.
Is the Švarc system prohibited or allowed?
The law must be regulated in some way, and if it prohibits something, then not even the prime minister of the government can prevent the office from acting, which has the obligation to carry out such checks and demand obligations.
You can say, “We change the law and we allow it,” but you can’t say that we will do as if nothing.
In the public procurement law, the regulations are quite strict as to the way in which it should be acted formally.
But, on the other hand, it is tragic that the candidate with the best offer is excluded for not meeting the formal requirements.
The law will never be perfect, but its application must be correct.This is, in my opinion, what we lack.
