Poland and the cosmos.
At the meeting of ministers of the countries of the European Space Agency held last week, Poland was accepted as the twelfth member of ESA. It is the second ESA member country of the former Eastern European bloc, after the Czech Republic, which became a full member on 12 November 2008).
Poland began an intense collaboration with ESA in 1994 and during the subsequent years participated in the agency’s project committee.
However, Poland’s journey to the cosmos began much earlier.
Polish enthusiasts were already engaged in space flights before World War II, although their work was not always understood.
I remember, for example, A. Šternfeld’s lecture at the Warsaw Astronomical Observatory in which, on December 6, 1933, he presented his ideas on the pioneering study “Introduction to Cosmonautics”.
The young engineer’s ideas (born 1905) left the attendees indifferent and, years later, Šternfeld recalled that Dr. Jan Gadomski had been the only one who had shown interest in his work.
In 1934 Šternfeld received in France the Robert Esnault-Pelterie and André Louis Hirsch Prize for his "Introduction to Cosmonautics".
Dr. Jan Gadomski (1899 - 1966), mentioned above, became later a major pioneer of astronomy and cosmonutics.
He published hundreds of articles in Polish journals and wrote a number of books devoted to this scientific discipline.
Gadomski became a promoter of cosmonautics, was known all over the world and his contribution to science was rewarded when one of the craters on the hidden side of the moon was named.
Already in 1925 a railway was built in Poland that would be equipped with a rocket engine.
Unfortunately, it is unknown who was the author of the proposal and neither are the details of the project known.
It is unclear whether the rocket was to be used for the launch of the dresin or for its braking.
The information about this dressing is limited to the collection in the press of the time.
From 1933 the Polish artillery began to dedicate itself to missiles.
The research was funded by Komórka Techniki Uzbrojenia in collaboration with Prof. Mieczyslawem Wolfkem and Prof. Gustawem Mokrzyckiegim.
From the preserved material, it is evident that the research has reached the stage of practical testing.
However, with the arrival of German troops, the investigation was interrupted.
In 1937 the prototype of a photoelectric fighter missile designed by the engineer Rohoziński appeared in the specialized press and the following year was published the study "Rakieta - torpeda powietrzna i rakietobomba lotnicza", by the author Leliwa-Krzywoblocki.
Both projects were intended for the military use of missile engines.
Shortly before the war, the provisional scientific advisory committee (Tymczasowy Komitet Doradczo-Naukowy) was responsible for all missile techniques projects for military use and coordinated all work.
The committee was founded in 1937, but after two years of activity, it was interrupted by the beginning of the war.
Other studies dedicated to cosmonautics appeared in the Polish press after the war thanks to the work of the Polish Astronautical Society (Polskie Towarzystwo Astronautyczne).
In the November 1954 issue of the magazine Problemy, society is first referred to with four very extensive articles dedicated to astronautics.
In one of them, Professor M. Subotowicze proposed the creation of a society that would be devoted to cosmonautics.
At that time artificial satellite projects had already been launched and it was obvious that cosmic research was a discipline with prospects for the future.
From the beginning of 1956 the Polish Astronautical Society (PTA) aspired to be part of the International Astronautical Federation (founded in 1951) and in the fall of that same year the PTA became a full member.
The following year the first president of the PTA, Kazimierz Zarankiewicz (1902 - 1959), became the vice president of the International Astronautical Federation.
He held this position until his death in 1959.
From 1956, the PTA participated significantly in the development of the RM probe rocket (Rakieta Meteorologiczna), which was a success and became the first Polish rocket in which scientific research was carried out.
The first type RM-1 was completed in 1957 and launched for the first time on October 10, 1958.
The rocket had a peak of 1,800 meters, about 80 cm in length and did not reach 5 kg of weight.
Later, the RM-1A version was completed and in the summer of 1959 air tests of the two-stage RM-2 rockets were started in the Błędów desert.
The rocket measured 1.4 meters and weighed about 11.5 kg.
The RM-34 rocket would have a peak of 14.5 km and its mission would be to control the wind of height.
However, in 1962 the work was suspended.
The successor to the first RM-type rockets was the Meteor-1 rocket, which was built during the years 1962 and 1965.
It was designed as a two-stage rocket, with a total length of 510 cm and an initial weight of 32.5 kg.
Three types (called Meteor-1A, -1B and -1C) were developed, which differed from each other by the space available for scientific devices.
On the Meteor-1A the space available for the volume was 0.4 liters, on the Meteor-1B 0.34 liters and on the Meteor-1C 0.62 liters.
The maximum peak in the three types was 37 km.
Between 1965 and 1968 the Meteor-2 rocket was developed at the Air Institute, with its first air tests started in October 1970.
The Meteor-2 rocket had an initial weight of 380 kg and was able to carry a useful weight of 10 kg up to 60 km in height.
Subsequently, the Meteor-2H and Meteor-3 versions were built.
It is necessary to mention also the entry of Poland into the COSPAR (Committee for Space Research) in 1960 and the formation of the national COSPAR committee two years later.
In the framework of the Interkosmos program, Poland joined space research on Soviet artificial satellites and, in 1978, the Polish pilot Miroslaw Hermaszewski became the second intercosmonaut after Vladimir Remek.
The suspension of the Social Work Act is not the solution.
Last week the Constitutional Court suspended the social labor law.
The resolution sparked heated debate in society.
It will be interesting to look at the existing problem from a broader perspective.
Liberal economic systems in the EU, as in the globalized world, are based on the principle of greater economic competition and less regulation.
Consequently, this means that the different economic forms and national economic systems are in permanent conflict with each other.
The cause lies in the principle of free trade and the free and unlimited movement of private capital, along with unstoppable financial speculation.
The effect of large differences in labor costs (wages) produces economic tensions.
Under this concept it is necessary to understand the situation in which the manufacturer, with the importation of cheap goods, tries to shorten distances and for this "provokes a drop" of the competitor's price with the aim of making up the largest part of the market and thereby increasing its margin of profits.
A large scale means, for most entrepreneurs, to move production abroad, buy there cheaper or disappear.The result is high unemployment in those countries where the price of labor, compared to other economies, is higher.
Because private capital has no social responsibility and is therefore not responsible for the unemployment this phenomenon generates, the social expenditure of the state necessarily grows.
All this situation favors the total disinterest of entrepreneurs to pay taxes and compensate for the economic and social damages they have caused in their desire to obtain profits.
The situation is universally so well known that no specific statistical data is needed.
The scrupulous practices of private capital create situations, in certain economies, in which the governments of these countries are forced to compete with the aim of artificially reducing the social level of the own population and thus attracting foreign capital to the country.
In other words, governments put private capital at the disposal of their own population without taking into account social decline.
This is evident especially in the changes in the current legislation.
The aim is to force the population to accept the dictates of private capital, especially with regard to wages.
This is achieved, on the one hand, through the system of economic obligation in the case of long-term unemployment; on the other hand, through the restricted right of employees with regard to labour rights.
The result is growing poverty along with increasing gaps between rich and poor.
For a number of years, there have been food delivery points in Germany for poor people who can’t keep up with their own work.
The number of people receiving this type of aid reaches a million.
In the framework of the increasing competitiveness of the German economy, a fairly frequent case occurs: people employed with a salary so low that the state must pay the rest to reach the minimum essential to survive.
A scandal of this type related to the situation of the auxiliary employees of the German federal parliament was made public.
People, pressured by an abysmal decline in their social level, are forced to emigrate as in the 19th century or to live badly with a terrible salary on the boundary of society, hoping that someday it will reach the private investor capital country.
Is it necessary to ask where it comes from?
In the case of other EU countries, then poverty passes from one country to another or never comes, since Chinese, Indians, Brazilians, Turks, Moroccans, Egyptians or Africans continue to work for a tiny portion of a European salary.
This also affects all of Latin America.
Liberal theories and the media say to the fullest that the state should not bring capital to the economy, that directing the economy leads to its failure.
Private capital defends with nails and teeth the thesis that the state should not intervene in the economy by entangling in control.
Then it is necessary to ask whether private capital does not influence with its selfishness the political march and, therefore, the entire state.
In this case, the answer is clearly affirmative.
The evidence is the existence of lobbies, in practice very powerful and ubiquitous, in all states.
The result is a desperate situation that manifests itself in the field of corruption, in mutual favors, in a legislation that is practically reproachable everywhere but is not punishable.
In Germany the situation is as follows: State ministries, in the absence of financial means, commission the drafting of bills to private legal firms, which are often linked to industry.
This type of bills are passed later in the Bundestag, the German parliament.
Thus, all power does not emanate from the people, as announced in the constitutions of Western democracies, but from the strong financial groups that represent their own interests.
It is obvious that democracies with a liberal orientation quickly find themselves in a situation such as that described by Appiános in his work The Crisis of the Roman Republic in the days of Caesar and Pompeii: "The state was long disintegrating and administrations were forcibly occupied."
In exchange for bribery, unlawfully obtained favors and aid to finance stones or swords.
The bribery and corruption spread without any impediment and the people went to the polls with the voting applauded in advance"... "there were no people with character who aspired to a position in the administration, so that once, because of this disorganisation, the state was eight months without consuls"... "It began to talk seriously that the only remedy for such a serious situation was autocracy and that it was necessary to choose a man energetic"... Although Appiános thought of Pompeii, César rose to power and transformed democracy forever into autocracy.
The conclusion, as in antiquity, is that today’s society is based on disregarded preferences of individual benefit without taking into account the common interests.
Private capital is not, in its essence, able to understand and claim the benefits of the whole society.
The result is the same as then, an unprecedented decadence of the elite, without any effort to reform it in depth.
The causes of the rise of fascist and communist regimes must therefore be sought in the unwavering liberalization of economic systems in the 19th and 20th centuries.
With regard to the current situation, it is possible to consider the disappearance of these systems for the benefit of a liberal-type democracy, as a definite pause, in anticipation of the next coup.
The really devastating fact is that the current elite completely ignores the losses of hundreds of thousands of lives, the social and humanitarian disasters we have witnessed, as well as the crimes against humanity, as we know them in ancient and recent history.
Suspension of the Public Procurement Act is not the solution; at least not in the long term.
Under pressure from economic competition, both internationally and within the EU, the Czech government will be forced to continue to seek other ways to reduce the social level of the population.
This trend is systematic.
The solution goes through concrete socio-political reforms, which reinforce both the participation of state capital and the influence of citizens in government and that weaken the monopoly position of private capital in society for the benefit of the state.
