Architectural study MVRDV demonstrates that true adventures are not just in the head - in the example of the Spijkenisse library and the newly completed "book mountain"- 2 photos
“I think the building is fun, it looks futuristic, and finally there’s something interesting to see,” says Lisette Verhaig, a passing person who passes through the street.
And Stefan Spermon, an IT technician at a large company located near the library, points out: “In addition, the building is beautiful.”
But I wonder why we need a library today.
We all have internet, tablets and e-books.
Nobody enters those old-fashioned libraries for pleasure, right?
Spijkenisse, a dormitory town located at the gates of Rotterdam that hardly deserves a fugitive visit, holds the dubious honor of having risen with a record to forget.
The population of 80,000 inhabitants has the lowest literacy rate in the Netherlands.
To counter this shameful situation, a few years ago it was decided to contribute somehow to general culture and copy the seven fictional bridges that appear represented on euro banknotes in the form of decorated armed concrete miniatures.
The success of the educational offensive was limited.
And so it was that the policymakers decided that there was only one possibility to improve statistics: a library had to be built!
Winy Maas, of the Dutch architectural studio MVRDV, a master in the art of bar diagrams and responsible for funny buildings at the same time as cynical, took the subject with his usual serenity and appeared at the presentation of the contest in 2003 with five books under his arm and a smile on his face.
And while the jury looked perplexed around him and shrunk his shoulders, Maas proceeded to stack the books by size forming a pyramid and concluded his brief speech with the following words: "Dear fellow citizens:
Here is my proposal for the book mountain of Spijkenisse, the so-called 'Boekenberg'.
Nine years later, the mountain of 30 million euros is raised in the planned place.
This is part of the revitalization project, which is completed with a underground parking, a supermarket, a post office and a couple of housing and housing buildings.
In early November, the book mountain was awarded the second prize "Best Library of NL 2012".
In addition, the project is also nominated for the "Dutch National Wood Award 2012".
In this way, the little city lacking in history, which until now had nothing more to offer than a postmodern pedestrian area and an incredibly ugly municipality behind whose white façade one would rather intuit a central dairy, now has a work of contemporary architecture.
But above all, Spijkenisse now has the first public cultural building in its history.
The Long Road to the Book
The first impression is that this is a book paradise under a cheese.
It is true that there is an elevator that transports us right to the center of this mountainous massive, but true lovers of space and reading do not use it, but prefer to merge with its topography at every step of its climb to the top.
The entirely glassy interior is bright and easy to see, the reckoned brick floor and the elegant lighthouses unambiguously support the public condition of the library.
The urban environment is perfect.
By raising the view you can see the banks of the park, the dogs and the boys and girls playing football.
And everywhere books, books and more books.
“Normally, bookstores are arranged along the façade and in the center an enormous dark room opens up that is usually somewhat uncomfortable and impersonal,” says Winy Maas.
What we have done is to put the classic spatial configuration on top and take the reading area from the inside to the outside.
The interior of the mountain is very well used: in the middle are the offices, the Internet library, the chess club, the environmental education center and the maintenance room.
Special mention deserve the black shelves that assume the functions of wall coating, parapet and barrier at the same time.
The sight, touch and smell are strange.
Even architects and civil engineers more daily shake their heads when they hear about this unknown material.
“We wanted to work with recycled materials,” explains Joop Trouborst, head of the project in the city of Spijkenisse.
And so it is like one day, in a Frisian farm, we find the right by-product from agriculture.
For many years, in the greenhouses and fields of the Netherlands, a few millimeters thick plastic fabric has been used as a base for sticking the roots of crops.
This is an inexpensive and efficient material.
This fine tissue lasts for two seasons and is then discarded.
For the library this fabric was pressed, for the first time in such amounts, to four centimeters thick plates.
With heat and pressure, the so-called agricultural plastic (KLP) changes colour and becomes a dark, homogeneous and resistant material that smells like a mixture of new car and sports shoe.
After 105 steps you reach the top of the mountain.
At the end of this continuous route of almost 500 meters around the mountain, the reward awaits us: from the cafeteria you not only have a fantastic view of the city, but you can also enjoy some delicious Dutch croquettes and their ficus planted in huge pots.
These create a pleasant atmosphere at the same time that they maintain the proper atmospheric humidity for this mountain of literature.
Donations for a New Soul
"Al it is hard to believe given its large glassy surfaces, this building is an exemplary project in terms of ecology," says Trouborst.
The necessary heating and cooling is obtained from geothermal energy.
Although the Book Mountain is located under a huge glass pyramid, even on the sunniest days the sun only shines for a few hours inside it.
The enormous wooden fences located in the transversal direction to the glass facade serve to shade and absorb most of the rays of the sun.
This creates a comfortable atmosphere.
The rest is about the automatic wheels.
Stefan Spermon, the skeptical information technology worker, has already dared to set foot in the new library.
Lisette Verhaig was there too.
Likewise, the professor of traditional Chinese medicine Cynthia Bogarde has visited the library. she qualifies the "Boekenberg" as Spijkenisse's "later soul".
The reason is that, on the occasion of the inauguration that took place a couple of weeks ago, all the inhabitants of the city were invited to donate a book from their private collection.
In this way it is intended to fill, for the time being, the optical gaps of a library that does not yet have its complete archive; it currently has 70,000 copies.
The concept is silent.
The shelves are full.
“There is nothing worse than a half-empty library,” says architect Winy Maas.
“I think that thanks to our initiative now all the inhabitants have a certain link with this building.
Everyone knows that your book is part of the library.
They are there just to decorate.
In this way, the MVRDV study has achieved all the success in that reigning discipline that in specialized argot is known as "creation of an identity".
The city of Spijkenisse has written a piece of the history of literature.
No matter how young and ignorant he may be.
Finally a starting point to reconstruct your identity.
