Germany abstained in the vote on the admission of Palestine.
According to Stephen Szabo, an expert on U.S.-Europe relations, this places Berlin in a rather sharp diplomatic position.
Deutsche Welle: Earlier this week, Germany said it would vote against the proposal to grant Palestinian territories the status of an observer state of the United Nations.
In the end, however, Berlin abstained.
And why ?
Stephen Szabo: Germany does not support what the Israelis have done in Gaza.
Now, because of the country’s special relationship with Israel, Germany must be careful.
But at the same time, I don’t think it supports the US position either.
Germany wanted to demonstrate its independence without being too critical of Israel.
During the uprising that took place in Libya in March 2011, Germany also abstained when it was about setting up a no-fly zone.
This has finally been declared by NATO.
Is it difficult for Germany to take a clear stance when important international issues are at stake?
Yes, it is so.
This is because at this time it is reorienting its foreign policy, moving away from a policy led, so to speak, by the United States and focusing on a German foreign policy.
And what makes things even more difficult is that Europeans do not have a coherent and uniform policy.
The Germans are at a crossroads.
They are expected to play a more independent role, but they are not used to doing so.
I think they are still trying to figure out what their role will be, but they have already begun the way toward a “normal” foreign policy.
A foreign policy similar to the countries such as France or Great Britain.
What exactly does “normal” foreign policy mean from the German point of view?
It is a policy that, when it comes to national interests, is willing to defend positions different from those of the United States or its European partners.
I believe that German foreign policy finds a strong motivation in economic policy, that is, in exports and in its relations with certain regions, such as Russia, China or the Middle East.
German economic interests are to a certain extent different from those of other great powers and for that reason Germany must protect its interests.
Have these economic interests influenced the position taken with respect to the conflict in the Middle East and the UN vote?
On the one hand, Germany has large markets in the Middle East, especially in the Gulf.
For this reason, it must be careful and not alienate itself from the Arab public opinion or the Arab elites.
This is important, of course.
But I would not give it so much importance since it is not a totally unilateral relationship.
However, they play a key role in German considerations.
Has Germany undermined its relationship with the U.S. by abstaining from voting on important decisions such as the Palestine vote?
I think that in Europe, and even in the United States, the German position enjoys an enormous degree of understanding.
For this reason, I don’t think there has been such a drastic breakdown as in the case of Libya.
Per with this Germany has managed to cultivate some respect.
After all, all this has only proved that it is a country that is taken seriously as an international actor and whose interests must be taken into account.
In Europe, there are different opinions about the Palestinian initiative.
Instead, the US has clearly shown itself in favor of a veto.
Is there a difference of opinion between the US and many European nations?
These disparities have always existed due to American domestic policy.
I think the Obama administration secretly shows a great understanding of the European position.
But, because of the political situation that is being lived here, it is obvious that the government cannot publicly defend that stance.
I think the real disparity of opinions does not actually have the magnitude that is attributed to it.
If we look at the relations between Obama and Israeli Prime Minister Netanyahu, we see that Obama is not enthusiastic about the policy he develops.
Is it difficult for Germany to reconcile its close relations with Israel and the United States, on the one hand, with the stance of its main partners in the EU, on the other?
I think that’s what makes it so difficult for the Germans.
Of course it would be a little easier for the Germans if there were a coherent and homogeneous European policy, but it is not the case.
Therefore, they do not have the possibility of being part of a higher entity, but they must drive things from their own position.
This is exactly what they are doing now with the euro.
I believe that in the future Germany will take on a leading role in forcing Europe to take a European stance.
Of course this is not easy for Germany, either simply because of the relationship itins with Israel.
This has always been a bitter topic.
But I think the Germans are clear that they should play the role of an independent figure.
Does Germany see itself in the role of a major international actor?
Or is it still difficult for you to accept that leadership?
Germany has not yet become accustomed, it is always somewhat uncomfortable and, for obvious reasons, it still costs the country to play a more important role.
If we look at the euro crisis, for example, we see that every time Germany positions itself as a leading actor, certain anti-German feelings are unleashed.
This is not easy for the Germans.
