When I grew up in Central California, I’ve been called “Mexican” all my life.
It’s ethnic tachigraphy, just as my friends in Boston refer to themselves as “Irish” or my friends in New York refer to themselves as “Italians.”
Later I decided for “Mexico-American.”
This was Mexico.
And, in my grandfather’s homeland, tachography or scripts were not needed.
He was simply American.
I speak Spanish well enough to handle myself during an interview in this language.
But I don’t have the level of vocabulary of a native and I can’t get rid of my American accent.
So I took my U.S. passport and put myself in the queue of foreigners.
I thought of that moment this week when Mexico’s elected president, Enrique Peña Nieto, visited the White House to meet with President Obama.
On the agenda, as always when the leaders of these two countries meet, it was: immigration, drugs and trade.
Peña Nieto was eager to talk also about the growth of the Mexican economy, one of the reasons why at this time it is as likely that a Mexican will stay in Mexico as he will venture to go to the United States.
He wants to partner with the United States and Canada and create in North America a trade bloc in the style of the European Union.
In addition, Peña Nieto promised to continue fighting the drug cartels in Mexico, although he did not give details.
For Mexico, the relationship with the United States is complicated and full of resentment.
Most Americans probably never remember that in 1848 the United States invaded Mexico and forced its leaders to surrender half of their territory to the point of a gun.
But for Mexicans, who think in centuries, not in minutes, the elements that remind them are everywhere.
So, in the moment a U.S. official says anything that brings the slightest criticism to Mexico, you start to hear complaints, both in the press and among the Mexican elite, about how the Americans are usurping the sovereignty of their neighbors.
And the sons of Moctezuma are put on war.
And yet, for Mexico, the relationship that really poses a challenge is the one they have with the more than 35 million Mexican-Americans living in the United States.
Are we talking about anger?
There is much.
In Mexico there are winners and losers, people for whom the country provides opportunities and others for whom it is not.
The only reason there are so many people of Mexican descent living in cities like Los Angeles, Las Vegas, Phoenix, Denver or San Antonio is that, at some point in our genealogy tree, there was a person, maybe the father or mother or some of the grandparents, to whom the door of opportunities in Mexico was closed and had to march north.
And most of the time that person fit into a certain profile: dark skin, a low level of education, from a poor people, etc.
We are their descendants and we are loyal to them.
Not in Mexico.
And, despite the fact that we are now living the American dream, having gone to good schools and having had good jobs, we can never lose sight of that what we are living is that, the American dream, and not the Mexican.
It is possible that sometimes our identity is not clear, but our loyalty is.
It is for the United States.
Moreover, we are aware that many of the Mexicans belonging to the ruling class elite do not like us.
The feeling is mutual.
They see us as a reminder of a humiliating defeat and look at us over our shoulders as if we were from an inferior category that is not Mexican enough.
Our Spanish will never be good enough and our ties with Mexico will never be strong enough.
In their view, our existence is synonymous with failure.
If our families hadn’t failed in Mexico, they’t have left.
And now we’t find ourselves trapped behind this silk curtain, living well in the United States but still as lonely souls.
My wife, who was born in Guadalajara and came legally to the United States when she was a child, reminds me that there is this fuss between the Mexicans and the Mexican-Americans because the first know with more solidity who they are and the second this annoys them.
Although she is a citizen of the United States, she considers herself part of both countries.
Meanwhile, many Mexican-Americans I know feel they’re not part of either.
We love listening to the Mexican band The Tigers of the North, but also Bruce Springsteen.
You have the best of each country, but you are not rooted in any of them.
In Mexico we are seen as Americans.
In the United States, we are considered Mexicans.
Now, to complicate things even more, so what I learned during my trip, some Mexican leaders and some intellectuals want to reconnect with the diaspora.
They want Mexican-Americans to work as improvised “ambassadors” of Mexico, representing their interests in the United States.
We would tell our American counterparts how fantastic it is to visit that country and we would pressure political leaders to strengthen their ties with Mexico.
Yes of course...
That will not happen.
There is too much resentment.
And, with wage inequality, galoping corruption and drug violence, many of us aren’t so sure it’s a fantastic country.
I am afraid you will be left alone with this idea, friends.
It is fair.
If some Mexicans are still not ready to forgive the United States for the way they treated Mexico a century and a half ago, then they have to accept the fact that some Mexican-Americans are still resented by how their relatives were treated far less time ago.
Hmmm .
Maybe we’re more “Mexican” than we thought.
