After examining the published research and putting the idea before a discussion group of 100 people, Professor Eastwood and colleagues defined boredom as the experience of "wishing, but not being able, to participate in an activity that fills you."
The difference between boredom and apathy is that the person does not do something but wants to do it.
It points out that with apathy there is no desire to do anything.
The main experience of boredom, he says, is “the alteration of the process of attention, associated with a low mood and a feeling that time passes slowly.”
Boredom can sound terribly similar to depression.
