Journalists' access to the summit information was restricted at all times.
During the day only broadcast, in the press room, the no-sound video of the presidential assembly with the message "private session, audio restricted".
The little information that circulated among reporters was delivered by the press spokesmen of some of the Unasur governments attending the meeting, although not the Peruvian.
The only document disclosed during the day was the list of assisting presidents, which caused the upset of hundreds of journalists from various national and international media that asked for more data.
Subsequently, the Peruvian Presidency sent an email to the media with the "final declaration" of the summit, but it is Humala's statement, and not the official document that closed the summit.
Last October, Peru hosted the 3rd South America-Arab Countries Summit (ASPA), and on that occasion, despite being insistently required by the press, the so-called Lima Declaration that they had previously announced was also not spread.
