Each week, students explore apocalyptic topics such as nuclear warfare, zombies, viruses and germs, and global warming.
This semester, when the professor of religion Stuart Charmé decided to teach a course on the end of the world, he knew he had an irresistible ankle: The end of the "long regressive count" of the Maya Calendar, on December 21, to which many people have clinged as a proof that the end of the world is coming.
But Charmé had no idea of what was waiting for him in the next couple of months: the cataclysmic Hurricane Sandy, a tax haven that some have called "deudarmagedon" and a growing conflict involving Israel, the place where end-time Christian theorists believe the Apocalypse will begin.
"I didn't realize this was going to be the most apocalyptic semester ever," Charmé told students at Rutgers-Camden University (New Jersey) this week.
If one looks at what has been happening in the world today as if we were 30 days away and counting, this has been a really good period.
And remember that evil is good for those of apocalyptic mentality.
And he’s not the only teacher offering courses on the “end of the world” this semester, in theory the latest in history.
At Temple, Assistant Professor Barry Vacker is teaching the course "Media, Culture and the End of the World".
Each week, students explore apocalyptic topics such as nuclear warfare, zombies, viruses and germs, and global warming.
“We analyzed why these ideas proliferate over time,” he said, and the way in which they offer hypothetical scenarios that guide certain human behavior.
If nuclear material falls into the hands of terrorists, for example, a war could break out.
This month, students looked at films with apocalyptic themes and explored how they compare them to real-life examples.
“I’ve tried to inform students about what’s possible, likely, credible, and impossible,” Vacker said.
On the main campus of the Pennsylvania State University, Latin American History professor Matthew Restall and his colleague Amara Solari, an assistant professor of Art History and Anthropology, have teamed up to teach a course, titled only “The End of the World.”
"We don't add '2012' to always count on the option of teaching the course again, in case the world doesn't end," Restall said.
Despite the “imminent ruin,” students must study, generate projects, and take final exams.
At Penn State, the final exam will be taken on the eve of the Apocalypse, leaving students no choice but to work “until the same night the world is supposed to end,” Restall said.
The courses were quite popular.
"It saturated in two hours," Restall said about his high-average student course, which filled up with 35 students.
We received email messages for weeks and weeks before the start of the semester, from people asking if there was still a place.
Students, for their part, assure that the course is one of the most interesting.
“I find it fascinating to see what people do to comfort themselves,” said Bridgid Robinson, a 23-year-old career student in Religion and Sociology from Haddonfield, New Jersey, in Rutgers-Camden.
And it is that apocalyptic mentality, secular or religious, is only a matter of consolation or its absence.
Will Wekesa, a 25-year-old career student of Psychology and Nursing, said he had seen all the apocalyptic movies.
“I had never heard of a class that could teach that,” he said.
I enjoy it.
But no student interviewed — much less a professor — said they believed in the December 21 expiration date.
“Our first project dealt with Maya prophecy and we somehow discredit it,” said Julie Zeglen, a 21-year-old graduate student at Temple and West Chester.
The Maya never predicted the end of the world; it’s just a key point on the calendar, Restall said.
But he noted that there is an apocalyptic anxiety in Western culture, which dates back several centuries, in which people react to the changes around them predicting the end of the world.
The Internet has caused a rise of these speculations.
“In other places people don’t think about this,” he said.
Especially in the English-speaking world.
Joseph Dougherty, a professor of religion at La Salle University who teaches courses in the Philippines this year, quickly answered the question of whether he knew about any course on the “end of the world” there.
"The Philippines is not involved in the end of the world," he wrote, insinuating an exception from a higher authority.
We have a pardon from the Pope.
Restall noted that over the years many days of the final judgment have been talked about, and said that if nothing happens on December 21, "people will begin to immediately think about the next date" or philosophize that December 21 is the beginning of a seven-year period after which the world will end.
Students and teachers are taking the date lightly.
Several said they were thinking of going to “the end of the world” parties.
“Maybe I’ll call some friends to laugh together,” said Samira Ford, a 20-year-old communications student.
